      public RepeatedByte setInternalArray(byte[] array)
      Gifts ownership of the supplied array and uses it as the internal storage array. Subsequent write actions may change the contents, and append actions may replace the internal storage array with something else.
      Parameters:
      array - array with valid data from zero to length
      Returns:
      this

    • array

      public final byte[] array()
      Provides access to the internal storage array. Do not hold on to this reference as it can change during a resize.

      The array may be larger than the amount of contained data, but the data is only valid between index 0 and length.

      Returns:
      internal storage array

    • setLength

      public final RepeatedByte setLength(int length)
      Sets the absolute length of the data that can be serialized. The internal storage array may get extended to accommodate at least the desired length.

      This does not change the underlying data, so setting a length longer than the current one may result in arbitrary data being serialized.

      Parameters:
      length - desired length
      Returns:
      this

    • addLength

      public final int addLength(int length)
      Sets the length to length + offset and returns the previous length. The internal storage array may get extended to accommodate at least the desired length.

      It is expected that users don't know the exact desired size, so the growth rate is the same as a generic ArrayList.

      See setLength(int)

      Parameters:
      length - added to the current length
      Returns:
      previous length
